==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: path
<hw>path</hw> <pr>(p⟦adot⟧th)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>paths</plw> <pr>(p⟦adot⟧⟦th⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[AS.
<ets>p⟦ae⟧⟦edh⟧</ets>, <ets>pa⟦edh⟧</ets>; akin to D. <ets>pad</ets>, G.
<ets>pfad</ets>, of uncertain origin; cf. Gr. <grk>pa`tos</grk>, Skr.
<ets>patha</ets>, <ets>path</ets>. ⟦root⟧21.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
trodden way; a footway.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The dewy <qex>paths</qex> of meadows we will tread.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A way, course, or track, in which anything moves or
has moved; route; passage; an established way; <as>as, the <ex>path</ex>
of a meteor, of a caravan, of a storm, of a pestilence</as>. Also used
figuratively, of a course of life or action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the <qex>paths</qex> of the Lord are mercy and truth.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. xxv. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>paths</qex> of glory lead but to the grave.</q>
<rj><qau>Gray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Path</ent>⟦br⟧

